'''Lazy linear hybrid automata''' model the [[discrete time]] behavior of [[control systems]] containing finite-precision sensors and actuators interacting with their environment under bounded inertial delays. The model permits only linear flow constraints but the invariants and guards can be any [[computable function]].
This [[computational model]] was proposed by [[Manindra Agrawal]] and P. S. Thiagarajan.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} This model is more realistic and also computationally amenable than the currently popular modeling paradigm of linear [[hybrid automaton]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
==External links== * [https://web.archive.org/web/20060827000728/http://www.comp.nus.edu.sg/~thiagu/public_papers/hscc05.pdf] Formalization and theory behind the model {{tech-stub}} [[Category:Automata (computation)]] [[Category:Models of computation]]

'''Penelope Jane Davies''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE}} is a Scottish mathematician who in 2009 became the second female president of the [[Edinburgh Mathematical Society]], after [[Elizabeth McHarg]].{{r|emspres|3pres}} Her research involves numerical simulation of the [[partial differential equation]]s describing [[Scattering theory|wave scattering]]. She is a senior lecturer in mathematics and statistics at the [[University of Strathclyde]].{{r|profile}}

Davies earned her Ph.D. in 1987 from [[Heriot-Watt University]]; her dissertation was ''Stability problems in nonlinear elasticity''.{{r|diss}}
She was on the staff of the [[University of Dundee]] before moving to the University of Strathclyde.{{r|dundee}}

Davies was made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire "for services to mathematics" in the [[2014 Birthday Honours]].{{r|bh}}

