[[File:Valérie Berthé.jpg|thumb|Valérie Berthé]]
'''Valérie Berthé''' (born 16 December 1968){{r|cv}} is a French mathematician who works as a director of research for the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]] (CNRS) at the Institut de Recherche en Informatique Fondamentale (IRIF), a joint project between CNRS and [[Paris Diderot University]]. Her research involves [[symbolic dynamics]], [[combinatorics on words]], [[discrete geometry]], [[numeral system]]s, [[tessellation]]s, and [[fractal]]s.{{r|irif}}

==Education==
Berthé completed her baccalauréat at age 16,{{r|ouest}} and studied at the [[École Normale Supérieure]] from 1988 to 1993. She earned a [[licentiate (degree)|licentiate]] and master's degree in pure mathematics from [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] in 1989, a [[Diplôme d'études approfondies]] from [[University of Paris-Sud]] in 1991, completed her [[agrégation]] in 1992, and was recruited by CNRS in 1993.{{r|cv}} Continuing her graduate studies, she defended a doctoral thesis in 1994 at the [[University of Bordeaux 1]]. Her dissertation, ''Fonctions de Carlitz et automates: Entropies conditionnelles'' was supervised by Jean-Paul Allouche.{{r|cv|mgp}} She completed a [[habilitation]] in 1999, again under the supervision of Allouche, at the [[University of the Mediterranean|University of the Mediterranean Aix-Marseille II]]; her habilitation thesis was ''Étude arithmétique et dynamique de suites algorithmiques''.{{r|cv}}

==Associations==
Berthé is a vice-president of the [[Société mathématique de France]] (SMF), and director of publications for the SMF.{{r|smf}}
She has played an active role in [[L'association femmes et mathématiques]].{{r|eige}}
Berthé has also been associated with the [[M. Lothaire]] pseudonymous mathematical collaboration on [[combinatorics on words]]{{r|lothaire}}
and the Pythias Fogg pseudonymous collaboration on [[substitution system]]s.{{r|fogg}}

==Recognition==
In 2013, Berthé was elevated to the [[Legion of Honour]].{{r|ouest|eige}}

